<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian Metropolitan Returns to Zagreb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20321A Zagreb VJESNIK in Serbo-Croatian 28 Jan 94 p 40 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20321A </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VJESNIK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by D.P.: "Metropolitan Jovan Returned to Zagreb"] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb -- Of the many Serbian priests who left their 
parishes following the aggression against Croatia, Jovan 
Pavlovic, Zagreb-Ljubljana metropolitan, returned to Zagreb on 
Thursday, becoming the first Serbian Orthodox priest to return 
to his diocese after a two-year absence. 
  Metropolitan Jovan was greeted by a large crowd of 
worshipers 
at the Church of the Transfiguration of the Lord in the center 
of Zagreb. He returned for the feast of St. Sava, one of the 
major holidays of the Serbian Orthodox Church. 
  The return of the Zagreb-Ljubljana metropolitan to his 
residence in Zagreb after a two-year absence spent in Belgrade, 
combined with visits to Ljubljana, has a deep meaning for global 
Croatian-Serbian relations as well as for normalization of 
relations following the signing of the Geneva Declaration by 
Franjo Tudjman and Slobodan Milosevic. Metropolitan Jovan is a 
Croatian citizen. He has a Croatian identity card and passport 
that were recently given to him personally in Ljubljana by 
Dalimir Vidis, an official of the Croatian Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs, in the name of the Committee for Normalization of 
Croatian-Serbian Relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

