<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Humanitarian Aid To Serbia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20300A Belgrade VECERNJE NOVOSTI in Serbo-Croatian 12 Jan 
94 p 9 </F>

<F P=103> 94P20300A </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade VECERNJE NOVOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by A.S.: "Russians Bring Aid"] </F>
  [Text] A plane from Russia with 22 metric tons of 
humanitarian aid for distressed children and humanitarian 
organizations in Yugoslavia and eastern Bosnia arrived at Surcin 
Airport yesterday afternoon. 
  The shipment contains 20 tons of food for babies and small 
children and two tons of indispensable medications such as 
penicillin, other antibiotics, and diarrhea remedies. Two-thirds 
of the shipment will stay in Yugoslavia; one-third will be 
distributed in eastern Bosnia, according to Lindel Sachs, 
spokesman for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees in Belgrade. 
  According to Mrs. Sachs, this is the first humanitarian 
shipment of food from Russia. Prior to this, only teams of 
drivers used to come from Russia to drive trucks through the war 
zones. 
  "Our office was accorded the honor of organizing the 
distribution of the shipment, which is always welcome in these 
regions," said Lindel Sachs. 
  The donor of this humanitarian aid is the State Committee of 
the Russian Federation for Elimination of Consequences of 
Natural Disasters and for Civilian Aid; the intermediary is the 
Russian Embassy in Belgrade; while the distributor is the UN 
High Commissioner for Refugees in Belgrade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

